<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF110-342-068  </DOCNO><DOCID>10 342 068.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  Dec 6 1990 n1242 p86(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DTI usability project aims to smooth computer interaction. (theUK's Department of Trade and Industry commences Usability NowProgramme)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The UK's Department of Trade and Industry (DTI) commences a 1.5million pounds sterling Usability Now Programme to makeinformation technology (IT) easier to use.andP;  Specifically, the DTIwants computer hardware and software suppliers, programmers andanalysts to utilize advanced technology and formal methods todevelop systems that are easier to use, have lower life-timecosts, have improved quality and generate higher profits.andP;  Thisrequires attention to the computer-user interface, how computersrelate to a company and how effectively they perform their job.andO;The new project will encourage users to be more demanding andexplicit on what they want in hardware and software.andP;  DTI will runhuman/computer interaction demonstration centers for the next twoyears.andP;  Other initiatives on the project are briefly noted.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Performance ImprovementUser InterfaceComputer SystemsUtilizationResearch and DevelopmentRequirements AnalysisGovernment FundingUnited KingdomGreat Britain. Department of Trade and Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>